My project uses an Arduino UNO with 11 LEDs connected to digital pins 2 through 12. 
Each LED has a resistor to protect it from too much current, 
and all the negative legs are connected to the GND of the Arduino through the breadboard.

The way it works is that the LEDs animate in two phases that repeat continuously. 
In the first phase, two LEDs light up at the same time one from the left end and one from the right end then turn off, 
and the next inner pair lights up, continuing until both sides meet at the middle LED. 
This creates a converging or closing-in effect. In the second phase, the animation reverses, 
starting from the middle LED and expanding outward toward both ends at the same time, 
creating an expanding or opening effect. These two phases loop continuously, 
giving the appearance of the LEDs bouncing back and forth from the edges to the center and back again.
